From: Ghaf contributors <ghaf@tii.ae>
Subject: [PATCH] synthesize the initial hotplug long-pulse at boot
 
On passthrough the host-owned DCE R5 emits the hotplug RM_EVENT only on a
real HPD edge. A panel already connected at gpu-vm boot generates no edge, and
any earlier event fired before the guest's RM_EVENT client registered -- so
nvDPNotifyLongPulse(TRUE) never runs, no SOR binds to the connector, and the
head has no output engine until the cable is physically replugged.

The event carries no payload: ReceiveHotplugEvent just schedules
nvHandleHotplugEventDeferredWork, which re-detects every connector. So schedule
that same deferred work once, right after the hotplug callback is armed.
Spurious pulses are normal on native (handler no-ops on no change), so this is
unconditional.
---
diff --git a/nvdisplay/src/nvidia-modeset/src/nvkms-rm.c b/nvdisplay/src/nvidia-modeset/src/nvkms-rm.c
--- a/nvdisplay/src/nvidia-modeset/src/nvkms-rm.c
+++ b/nvdisplay/src/nvidia-modeset/src/nvkms-rm.c
@@ -1786,6 +1786,16 @@
                         "Failed to register display hotplug "
                         "handler: 0x%x\n", ret);
         }
+
+        /* Passthrough: the host-owned DCE only sends hotplug events on a
+         * real HPD edge, so a panel already connected at boot never
+         * produces one. Deliver the initial long-pulse ourselves: same
+         * deferred work a real event schedules, delayed so device init
+         * finishes first. */
+        (void) nvkms_alloc_timer_with_ref_ptr(
+            nvHandleHotplugEventDeferredWork,
+            pDispEvo->ref_ptr,
+            0, 2000000 /* 2s */);
     }
 
     // Allocate a handler for the DisplayPort "IRQ" event, which is signaled
